President Joe Biden has announced his intent to nominate two individuals for key diplomatic positions in his administration. The first nominee is Philip S. Goldberg, who currently serves as the U.S. Ambassador to the Republic of Colombia. Goldberg is a career member of the Senior Foreign Service and has held various diplomatic positions throughout his career, including Ambassador to the Philippines, Ambassador to Bolivia, and Chief of Mission of the U.S. Office in Pristina, Kosovo. He has also served as the Senior State Department Fellow at Georgetown University and as the State Department's Coordinator for the Implementation of United Nations Resolution 1874 on North Korea Sanctions. Goldberg earned a B.S. degree from Boston University and achieved the rank of Career Ambassador in 2018. He has received several awards for his service.

The second nominee is Carrin F. Patman, who currently chairs the Metropolitan Transit Authority of Harris County, Texas. Prior to her current role, Patman worked as a trial lawyer for three decades, handling major litigation involving commercial disputes, securities matters, antitrust and competition issues, and regulatory compliance. She has also been actively involved in civic engagement, serving on various boards and organizations, including the Houston Chapter of the International Women's Forum and the Greater Houston Partnership. Patman earned her B.A. from Duke University and her J.D. degree from the University of Texas School of Law. She has received multiple awards for her work, including the Karen H. Susman Jurisprudence Award.

Both nominees will be serving as Ambassadors Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary, with Goldberg being nominated for the Republic of Korea and Patman being nominated for the Republic of Iceland.